  "prompt": "Why is it that forms in the US that ask for your race/ethnicity also ask in a separate question if you consider yourself Latino/Hispanic?",
  "response": "This is because \"Hispanic/Latino\" is considered an ethnicity, not a race, in the U.S. Census and many other official forms. Someone who is Hispanic/Latino can be of any race - white, Black, Indigenous, Asian, etc. \n\nFor example, a person from Mexico could racially identify as white, Black, or Indigenous, while still being ethnically Hispanic/Latino. This is why these categories are often asked as separate questions to capture both racial and ethnic identity more comprehensively.\n\nThe distinction stems from how the U.S. government and statistical agencies have historically categorized population demographics, attempting to provide more nuanced data about racial and ethnic diversity.",
